The Vice President of the United States, Mike Pence, delivered remarks at the First Baptist Church of Scottsdale in Scottsdale, Arizona. He expressed his appreciation for the warm hospitality and discussed the exciting time for the economy of Arizona and the nation. Pence highlighted the achievements and contributions of the Hispanic American community, including record low unemployment rates and job creation. He emphasized the administration's commitment to creating more opportunities for Hispanic Americans and promoting economic growth. Pence was joined by Governor Doug Ducey, Senator Martha McSally, and Treasurer Jovita Carranza, who also spoke about the economic success and growing influence of the Hispanic community in Arizona. The conversation also touched on the importance of the United States-Mexico-Canada Agreement (USMCA) for further economic growth and job creation. Pence assured the audience that the administration will continue to fight for the opportunities of Hispanic Americans to live the American Dream.